The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classics at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be waiting long.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that the Czech mobile service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ telecommunications authority, which drew attention to the fact that the price of an SMS here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
According to the final steps taken by the European Commission in the area of roaming fees, it is likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers from the Czech mobile providers SMS will be cheaper from abroad than at home.
How come the prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of well over 100%.
On the other hand, mobile operators like to beg on the fact that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past had often said that there was no place for another supplier in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with their own network will no longer have a lot of opportunities (at best he would probably find few more frequencies).
But there is one more option - a virtual provider.
In particular, the entry into the mobile market of virtual providers brought a significant price reduction, to which classic mobile providers also had to respond.
There were similar votes on the UK market prior to the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be really successful.
By the way, you don't need to look for examples for long.
In February of this, we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers, thus raising to the country's five largest provider.
The financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind the mobility.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilizing in Poland shows, it can also be quite a good move to focus on a non-clinical target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Echte Kerle select Mobility - the provider they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept could take its foot in the Czech Republic, as in Poland.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
It is also relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic chanceslos, the mobile operators think
However, it is almost certain that when a virtual mobile provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobilizing.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look particularly hopeful.
There will be a market entry of mobility in other countries of our region," says a phone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly she confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly attached to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can not create a potential competitor.
For some time now, their interest in a start of a virtual mobile provider has been showing the group GTS Novera, who wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
"We have a great interest in providing our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile communications providers.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve progress in negotiations," said the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
Until now, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities vis-à-vis other markets.
So far, no subject has yet addressed us with a complex and serious project in this field," says his explanation for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Srše from Telefónica O2.
Other providers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová, in rare agreement with the O2 statement, adds: "We have not yet found a viable and both beneficial project to which one could build on."
And she adds: "The network of T-Mobile will hardly show up a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this moment we must already have a concrete offer to think so short-term."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to look for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider was called more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thereby also to a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor to enter the market?
That the providers can pull on a strand when it comes to something, also proves the long way around the origin of U:fon.
The probably strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the moment when U:fon came to the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This also demonstrates the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now just U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently further strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high requirements on the market itself and above all on its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTU, which unfortunately - unlike the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
But this related to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The entry into the market of a virtual mobile phone provider would then be possible after a contract concluded between a mobile phone provider and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic suppliers," said Kristián Chalupa, in his reply to our request from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a wording would not surprise representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying by an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, by ensuring that nobody abuses his position on the market.
In particular, when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Where virtual providers work normally abroad, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, probably the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a reduction in prices do not belong to the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking to see that the three mobile providers are almost already in line with their reactions.
The question whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolute price of petrol at the gas stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this case that indicate a anti-competitive action, and thus has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market for virtual providers are probably missing from the telecommunications regulatory authority," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the approval of the network operator is always necessary for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And, logically, the mobile service provider has the monopoly for his network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if one does not go along with this argument, it should be at least a warning to the ÚOHS that three mobile providers are noticeably similar.
In doing so, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera) demonstrate that they face very similar obstacles during negotiations with all suppliers.
The elimination of responsibility for the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS is dissociated from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recent adoption of the Telecommunications Act failed to implement the extension of the ČTU's competence in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know that only too well, but they are likely to have other interests.
It's okay if no one looks at you.
The functioning of any pseudovirtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unobserved.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Normally, they are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile phone services, for example, offer Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic companyman who ordered a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile communications providers prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not happen to the responsible mobile providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
In fact, from the activity of these companies they do not have to be neglected profits, at the same time they are not affected by the actual official marketing - unlike the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický points to possible problems: "The law allows for such kinds of speculations, despite all that the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
These must also accept that the SIM card does not run on its name on its phone, so they cannot fully have it as the normal customers of the mobile service providers."
But this alone, the ČTÚ would at least have to be strange.
A further question for the ÚOHS is also opened.
Do the mobile operators close their eyes before such action, why do they block themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to discover such activities, and if it does not, it does not have to be satisfied with the provider’s declaration that they know nothing about them and their terms of business would prohibit them.
When the Czech Republic No longer is the most expensive
As has been pointed out several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers has brought about a significant price decline in the various services.
In doing so, practically all countries where virtual providers are formed have tried to prevent the formation of classic suppliers virtually more or less.
The arguments used by them were virtually identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies, which in no way tried to protect the interests of mobile telephone providers, intervened in these moments.
Whether it was through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and this was followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies all the way to a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we can't get rid of the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile phone market may soon move back into motion.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile phone provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other interested parties (to discriminate).
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
