These can currently be purchased about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Guests can buy a 30-day, 90-day or an annual coupon (as valid from 1 January 2009) at the same time on their chip card, in the information centres and branch offices of the transport companies at the Muzeum Metro Stations, Můste, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Let the cantony, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
The coupons have also been available on the pages of the traffic companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers up to the afternoon hours.
Those who use internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they had to wait regularly for their paper tickets in long queues.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the Opencard in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these places there is also a switch with trained staff available to the traveler, who advises interested persons on the internet and also plays the coupon on the card," says the speaker of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons can also be played at self-service machines on the Opencard, which are mounted in some subway vaults.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, remembering ticket values, the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"At the moment there are five of them in the city, but it is to be eighty by the end of the year," Opatrný adds.
The coupon controls instead of the driver an automatic machine
The operation of the machines that will function from tomorrow is easy.
You only have to insert the chip card, and the pre-acquired coupon plays itself.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the main towns and on the bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, with which the inhabitants from the municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia enter the capital.
"In the trains that are integrated with Prague, the train companions have read equipment that enables them to check the validity of coupons by time and zone," explains Filip Drápal from the organization Ropid. This organization compiles the schedules for Prague transport companies.
The suburbs have ticket reading equipment at the ticket desk at the driver's desk.
When entering, the chip card must not only be shown at the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position at the side of the checkout.
The driver thus controls the validity of the charged coupons.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the charged coupons, nothing is easier than the driver to ask for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not drive out of town buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends, can go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information for the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
