I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove this so far where we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we may at least hope, as all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we turn to other species and cut questions of feeling or generally of consciousness, we enter an inescapable terrain because the hardware does not match.
If a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it kills, escapes or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists conclude a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe that.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
On the one hand, the almost always associated circuits with the human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal Cortex (because of its involvement in the short-term memory and in the execution / control functions).
This wide region is much higher in humans than in other primates and seems to be totally lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness which depend on the prefrontal Cortex, including the knowledge we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is therefore reason to assume that man is even different from the other primates.
Another dramatic characteristic should be the linguistic nature of man: Since such a large part of his experience is connected with language, it often says that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even though consciousness does not depend on language, it would certainly affect it, so animal consciousness, as it may be, may be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to determine how consciousness in other animals may look.
If, as something internal and subjective, it is neither measured nor, because of the special hardware, can be analysed based on our own experience, his research presents us with great problems.
Most of my comments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is more scientifically accessible.
One could investigate the animal consciousness processes without regard to their contents, and that is exactly what happens in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one shifts to the neural correlates of consciousness rather than to the causal mechanisms: both might be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal Cortex for the condition of visualization.
What is the result of the sensations?
I take it back that an emotional system like that of fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
