Among scientists, a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion for years - the swing-by-anomaly.
The Swing-by is a flight maneuver of space probes in which they receive additional vibration in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
As a result, the probes can save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the Sunny Ulysses.
What the researchers have been wondering about for years, however, is that the aircraft do not behave 100 percent the way one would expect according to the old-fashioned gravitational law.
On the contrary, irregularities occur in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly faster or slower.
So far, physicists have not been able to explain this effect.
They baptized him Swing-by-Anomaly.
Some experts fear that the general theory of relativity of Albert Einstein, which describes the attraction of matter through a curvature of space, could not be quite right.
The American physicist Stephen Adler from the Institute for Advanced Study from Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not mistaken, and he tries to explain the swing-by-anomaly by means of the so-called dark matter that astronomers in the universe have made up.
"Responsible for the anomaly could be dark matter, which could also be very close to the earth," he writes.
The space researchers have only been aware of the existence of dark matter for about ten years.
From it is obviously an attraction whose effect on other celestial bodies can be observed.
On the other hand, it itself is completely invisible, that is, it sends and reflects no electromagnetic radiation, especially no visible light.
According to the calculations of the scientists, the dark matter always makes up a fifth of the whole mass of the universe.
