Bilingual training debate: Education in English-speaking surroundings
In this issue of the Education Watch, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the positions of the candidates for bilingual training.
Lance T. Izumi, a leading scientific assistant in California's studies and senior director in the field of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is a co-author of the book "Not as good as you think: Why the middle class needs a school choice".
Addressing the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's election campaign mentions that "the probability of afro-American and Hispanic students successfully closing the school is lower than in white students" - which is true.
In order to close this performance gap, Obama's educational plan recommends specifically among others a bilingual transition phase in training for those who first learn English.
However, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which focuses on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the distance in schooling.
Let's take as an example "Sixth Street Prep", a primary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, amazing 100 percent of the fourth class students passed the state exam in Mathe at a good level.
Also surprisingly, 93 percent of children from the fourth year of school were rated well in the English exam.
This amazing success was achieved with other methods than those preferred by Obama.
The School of Sixth Street focuses on review and exercise, on continuous control of knowledge and an attitude that does not tolerate exceptions.
