Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its President, Dr Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Given this drama and the dissatisfaction of the public, in February 1994, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever, who had the objective of bringing light into the circumstances that led to such tragedy, and working out guidelines to prevent a renewed disaster of this kind.
