`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of the people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Due to the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and through work in this area during the following years, we have regained public confidence," she says before she proudly emphasizes that almost 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec in early 2008.
However, Dr. Décary is aware that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has acted according to the principle of caution.
At this time, we experienced the occurrence of numerous cases of human form of cattle in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since the founding of 1998.
"And we didn't have the slightest idea whether this disease could be transmitted over the blood.
So let us call on one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, which we believe is to use exclusion measures, if you don't know this and if a disease progresses slowly, as it is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, blood was not taken from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, some years ago, without any doubt, this disease was proved to be transmitted over the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution we used has a meaning.
In 1999 a much more precise technology was published on the market to detect HIV: The nucleic acid tests (NST) which enable the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST allowed to shorten the incubation time between the time when the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be demonstrated by our techniques in the blood, explains the specialist.
This time could be reduced to less than a week.
Thus, the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it, and one could not recognize it, was reduced significantly.
These improvements allowed to significantly reduce the risk of transferring AIDS via blood transfusion.
Nowadays, one out of 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV infected blood.
In other words, you need to distribute 12 million blood cans before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood canned every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transmitted over a blood can.
I think that today you can feel comfortable getting or writing a blood transfusion in order to restore health, says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We need to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues before she emphasizes that Hema-Quebec needs to provide sufficient care in addition to safe supply.
'The need is increasing because the population is ageing.
Since cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or blood patches.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which, on average, includes only 3% of the population of Quebec, suitable for blood donation. '
In doing so, any healthy person 18 years of age or older can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who make their blood available are not accepted because they are ill, for example, AIDS or malaria, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is spread are excluded for one year.
With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can't donate any more blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep them and to make them become regular donors.
