This is confirmed, and pursues an orthodox logic that the world's largest gold-winning society sought a slanderous complaint of more than six million against three authors and a small medium-sized publishing house with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of slanderous charges, but the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely silenced by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to take everyone into the ruins who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the process proceeds, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very uneven weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactic of these uneven struggles is, moreover, often to ruin the defenders in order to force a common settlement that makes the opposite side mouth-to-mouth and also deters anyone who dares to re-examine the question.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she should have presented her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast to what is going on in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates are usually held through the exchange of ideas and not by batons.
So it would have been sufficient if the gold mine had revealed their books and files and opened a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent testing teams that could have brought light to this question.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have any confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he can at the same time ask for a 'public' debate, while at the same time denying the opinions of this public?
It seems that this word in the Vice-President's world covers only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a very narrow view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't understand - is that the public who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada is doing this primarily because she rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is ready to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not in a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the `public debate', Barrick Gold has just addressed the authors of Noir Canada, in which she requires them not to use that term anymore...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's action is a direct attack on the freedom of academic research and the sense of truth, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denys the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of the world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could lead it by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment we belong to has long been able to deal with debates and inconsistencies and resolve conflicts.
The disproportionate action of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, unlike what it is proposing, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the university world, as well as to the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures that limit this kind of unjust actions.
