The psychology of surrender - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, buyers tend to spend more and thus overvalue the bid.
Neurologists and economics researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves in competition, such as auctioning on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto while the other took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the volunteers were investigated by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
During both games the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of Striatum, a complex below the cirrhosis, was measured in the case of losers of the auction, in which the opponent's surrender plays an important role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-remuneration" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase could be explained by avoiding overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have also carried out investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should participate against one partner under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product, after which they made their operations.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars reward in case they came out of the game as winners.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which in the case of a lost game was also lost.
The difference between the two groups thus consisted merely in the emphasis on one being on winning, while the other was on losing.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, the members of the "opposite losing" group were ready to go beyond those in the control or "win" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
In fact, the behaviour observed at auctions has so far been based only on the joy of winning or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should the doctor be visited?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated to be one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver disease caused by various viruses.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but pathogens and diseases differ.
Depending on the pathogen, hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (e. g. sperm, sheath secret or saliva).
Travellers are recommended vaccination against the viruses A and B anyway, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms in hepatitis A occur approximately two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by unwelling, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Afterwards the jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and recovery may last for up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, approximately 1 million people die from hepatitis B, which has been caused by liver cancer and cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every 10th infected person is in medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated liver cirrhosis and liver cancer can result.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms occur after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspection, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who have undergone a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable during routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the home doctor with the first signs of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured, the virus can be exterminated, thereby preventing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
September 30th is the world day of hepatitis, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen the awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As latest research shows, religious faith acts like a type of "smart" which should have facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Researchers at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It was investigated to what extent belief in God affects human pain, reported the British sheet "Telegraph".
In the course of the more bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that Catholics could activate the part of their brain responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, besides scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participated.
When trying, the subjects were attached to the left hand a sparkling device, which gave off the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: on the one hand, a picture of the Mother of God painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would create some kind of religious trance among the faithful, while they chose da Vinci's image because it was hardly distinguished from the other painting and felt calming.
The test subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and at this time they received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while looking at either the religious, or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "in security" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "concerned" and they had felt "rest and peace".
While looking at the religious painting, they reported about 12% less pain than if they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be caused by other, highly active images among the atheists, but one would just have to find the corresponding photo.
"We need to find an image that causes very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and also do it in many cases," says Wright.
After these excellent results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
