Intelligent car imitates the flight of the hummel
What would be the best way to develop new technologies to prevent accidents if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers from Hummeln were inspired in the creation of new accident prevention systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the B23C type-controlled biomimetic system, a mini car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protector's shield", said Kazuhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can be seen in any direction and at an angle of more than 300 degrees, plays an important role.
In order to imitate the function of the compound eye, the researchers picked up the idea of the laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a 180-degree field of vision within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor to board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in fractions of seconds, and the robot immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of bees by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place instinctively.
"If it wasn't that way, the robot couldn't react fast enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyauki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees when they avoid other bees.
And this has to be done in a fraction of a second.
However, in contrast to bees, it can only be two-dimensional, not up, down, or even diagonal, only in the direction of the reversibility of the tires.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoid other bees, the researchers could only use the rotational movement, or the acceleration and deceleration of the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life span than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it is based on the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react accordingly to them.
It does not have to store them, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it constantly takes only a handful of KB Memory.
There is no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which is estimated by Nissan to be in production within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately directing the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to the target.
