"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening in the major urban centres of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multi-story complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the hall cinema in the center. A process that not only appears to be inevitable and irrevocable but also carries the lives of a cultural crime.
In most cases, historical places are filled with memories, "it's like losing a friend with whom you've put back a piece of street full of emotions," said the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great prize of Cannes 20 years ago. It's the story of a suburbs kinos and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a probably lost cinema world.
The figures supplied by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; for the most part, these stamps paid the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main innocent are multiplexkinos, because they are just these three regions where the largest number of these modern cinemas has been recorded: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has led the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of Anec, "it is useful that new structures arise, but first of all the preservation of the already existing, because closes a hall in the city, not all its regular customers are ready to visit instead of the old one multiplex cinema in the periphery.
And here is still the missing budget for the fund of the trade association eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
In order to obtain the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be necessary in the year".
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinema halls, has decided to protect it through an agreement between the municipality and Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public regarding local transport: it will be allowed to drive to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and to park at more favourable parking charges.
"It's a pleasant initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope other cities will join our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, however, we also need better audio and video equipment to work against the superpower of multiplex halls, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closing of Baghiera's "Supercinema", the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to form the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the thought for 10 years.
For 25 years I have lived in Rome; if I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
