When the energy emerges from the waves, suddenly the big ones run on
It is a non-exhaustive source of money that covers more than 70% of the planet's surface and only now do these seem to be the great energy companies in the world to understand.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that are now all looking at, and also looking for octopus, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and examined for 70 years; not by chance these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil broke around 1980, the idea of marine energy was lost, but now the environmental organisations and the increased oil price are pressing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy demand could be covered by the ocean waves' energy.
This would be equal to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would come.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the construction of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry that rely on marine energy generation.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – according to the spokesman of a company known to the American giant in the Wall Street Journal – and considers the possibility of working with us."
This is about the procurement of approval from the American Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is not an underestimating sign, especially when considering that oil continues to be funded by the US in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which invest in the new industry, are also not known, so observers speak of an increasing interest.
Even improved technologies.
Experts are talking about a technology still in progress, not least because the last doubts of environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are rather small and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater impact on the environment need to be developed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power uses for example a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which move the buoys up and down, is transformed into hydraulic pressure within the swimmer via pistons and cylinders.
It drives a turbine, which in turn runs a generator.
The current is then sent via underwater lines to the coast.
So far, there are four planned installations of this kind, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy obtained could also serve for military facilities.
However, Verdant Power already produces energy for a department store and a parking space with the help of undersea turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tide drive the turbines which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Recovery Research, a particular interest immediately deserves the potential that lies in the tides.
Although this is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are better predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of electricity.
Especially the tide energy is what states like New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states made it possible to invest already $7.5 million in 2008 – up to 35 million are planned for 2009.
